pq:text.pq:tspan: Hi Kate, Abbey! What are you up to?
We are trying to simplify our game
CooL! I was wondering, is there any way to separate Bugs functionality?
Yes! We can have bugs as objects.
What is an object?
An object is a thing in our program that we can interact with. Each object will know certain things, and be able to do things…
Hmm… So, if we want to have all the functionality that relates to our bugs in one place we need to create A Bug object?
Exactly! To do this we create a Bug class, its like a template from which our bugs will be created.
Ok… so to create an object all we need to do is Dim myBug as Bug, right?
Nearly! You actually need to create the objects using new… So, we need to type myBug = new Bug. This creates a new bug that we can interact with using the myBug variable.
So what goes into the Bug class?
The bug class will have fields to store data, and methods to create its behavior. We will also need a constructor, which sets up the data within the object when it is created.
So, we can have basic functionality for our bug, like draw and update inside the constructor?
No, we need to have two more subs which will do that for us.
Hmm… I’m not sure that I understood it completely… Let’s try it out to see how it does work…
wow… That was interesting… But our bug goes off the edge…
It’s easy to fix. We just need to create a new sub inside the Bug class which will be responsible for checking whether our bug does not goes off the screen
Great idea!
Something called like CheckCollisions() sub?
Can’t wait to try it….
